A toilet flushing mechanism is an internal system that regulates water storage, deployment, and replenishment to clear waste from the bowl. 
The process relies on a combination of gravity, siphonic suction, and mechanical valves working in tandem.The Flushing Process Step-by-Step
The mechanical sequence happens in three major phases over roughly 10 to 15 seconds:
Activation: Pressing the handle or button pulls an internal lever or pushes a pneumatic rod. 
This action lifts the flush valve (either a rubber flapper or a plastic canister tower) off the drain seat at the bottom of the tank.
The Flush: Gravity rapidly dumps the tank's water volume into the bowl in under three seconds. Water exits via the rim holes and a targeted siphon jet at the base. 
This sudden influx forces water up and over the integrated U-shaped trapway pipe behind the bowl. 
Once water fills the trapway, it creates a vacuum siphon that forcefully sucks waste out into the main sewer line. 
Air eventually enters the trapway, breaking the suction and creating the familiar gurgling sound.
The Refill: As water leaves the tank, the fill valve float drops. This action opens the inlet fill valve to pull fresh water from your home supply line. 
The flapper falls back down to seal the drain hole so the tank can fill up again. 
Concurrently, a small refill tube diverts a portion of water straight down the overflow pipe to restore the normal standing water level inside the bowl. 
Once the rising float reaches its target height, it cuts off the water supply.

